        <li><strong>Health:</strong> Non-porous surface won't absorb food odors or tomato sauce stains. Zero risk of chemical leaching when heated.</li>
        <li><strong>Versatility:</strong> Often oven-safe (without the lid), allowing you to bake and store in the same vessel.</li>
        <li><strong>Durability:</strong> Doesn't warp or degrade in the dishwasher over time.</li>
        <li><strong>Drawbacks:</strong> Heavy to carry in a backpack, breakable if dropped, and generally more expensive.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="gp-box">
      <h3>Plastic Containers</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Portability:</strong> Extremely lightweight and perfect for commuting to work or the gym.</li>
        <li><strong>Durability:</strong> Shatterproof. Dropping them usually only results in a cracked lid at worst.</li>
        <li><strong>Cost & Space:</strong> Cheaper to buy in bulk and usually stack much tighter in cabinets.</li>
        <li><strong>Drawbacks:</strong> Can absorb smells (like garlic), stain easily (like curry), and degrade faster with repeated microwave use.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Essential Buying Features</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Leak-Proof Lids:</strong> If you commute with your food, a silicone gasket and locking tabs are mandatory. Snap-on lids (like standard Pyrex) will leak soup into your bag.</li>
    <li><strong>Compartments:</strong> Single-compartment containers are more versatile for large meals like pasta or salads. Multi-compartment containers are better if you dislike food touching or need precise portion control for macros.</li>
    <li><strong>Nesting:</strong> If you have limited kitchen storage, ensure the containers nest inside one another. Containers with thick glass walls often don't nest well.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-list">
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Are glass meal prep containers better than plastic?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Glass containers are generally considered better for longevity and health. They are non-porous (so they don't absorb stains or odors), microwave and oven-safe, and environmentally friendly. High-quality BPA-free plastic is better for portability because it is lightweight and won't shatter.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">How long does meal prep last in the fridge?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Most cooked meals will last 3 to 4 days in an airtight meal prep container in the refrigerator. Seafood should ideally be eaten within 2 days. For longer storage, freeze your prepped meals.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Can I microwave plastic meal prep containers?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">While many plastic containers are labeled 'microwave-safe', it is generally recommended to microwave food in glass or ceramic to avoid potential chemical leaching, even with BPA-free plastics. If using plastic, never microwave it with the lid sealed tightly to prevent warping.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What size meal prep container should I buy?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">For a standard adult portion (protein, carb, vegetable), a 28 oz to 36 oz (about 3.5 to 4.5 cups) container is ideal. Smaller containers (12-16 oz) are good for snacks or small salads.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Are compartmentalized containers worth it?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Compartments (like bento boxes) are great if you prefer your foods not to touch or if you are packing a cold side (like fruit) alongside a hot main dish that you plan to heat separately. However, single-compartment containers offer more flexibility for bulky meals.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Related Resources</h2>
  <div class="related-grid">
    <a href="/air-fryer-cooking-times" class="related-link">
      <h4>Air Fryer Cooking Times</h4>
      <p>Cheat sheet for perfectly cooked meals</p>
    </a>
    <a href="/recipe-calorie-calculator" class="related-link">
      <h4>Recipe Calorie Calculator</h4>
      <p>Calculate macros for your meal prep</p>
    </a>
  </div>
</div>

<script is:inline>
  const headers = document.querySelectorAll('th[data-sort]');
  const rows = document.querySelectorAll('.brand-row');
  const tableBody = document.getElementById('tableBody');

  // Sort logic
  headers.forEach(header => {
    header.addEventListener('click', () => {
      const sortType = header.getAttribute('data-sort');
      const isAsc = !header.classList.contains('asc');

      headers.forEach(h => { h.classList.remove('asc', 'desc'); });
      header.classList.add(isAsc ? 'asc' : 'desc');

      const rowsArray = Array.from(rows);

      rowsArray.sort((a, b) => {
        let aVal, bVal;

        if (sortType === 'brand') {
          aVal = a.children[0].innerText.toLowerCase();
          bVal = b.children[0].innerText.toLowerCase();
        } else if (sortType === 'material') {
          aVal = a.children[1].innerText.toLowerCase();
          bVal = b.children[1].innerText.toLowerCase();
        } else if (sortType === 'compartments') {
          aVal = a.children[2].innerText.toLowerCase();
          bVal = b.children[2].innerText.toLowerCase();
        } else if (sortType === 'microwave' || sortType === 'dishwasher' || sortType === 'leak') {
          const colIndex = sortType === 'microwave' ? 3 : (sortType === 'dishwasher' ? 4 : 5);
          aVal = a.children[colIndex].innerText.includes('✓') ? 1 : 0;
          bVal = b.children[colIndex].innerText.includes('✓') ? 1 : 0;
        } else if (sortType === 'price') {
          aVal = a.children[6].innerText.length; // Compare number of '$'
          bVal = b.children[6].innerText.length;
        }

        if (aVal < bVal) return isAsc ? -1 : 1;
        if (aVal > bVal) return isAsc ? 1 : -1;
        return 0;
      });

      rowsArray.forEach(row => tableBody.appendChild(row));
    });
  });
</script>

